{#- VARIANT DETAIL (definition) — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-balances-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Balances wrong after conversion, plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>When balances are wrong after a QuickBooks Desktop to Online migration, the usual culprits are opening balances that didn&rsquo;t convert correctly, dropped or duplicated transactions, reconciliation status that didn&rsquo;t carry, accounts-receivable and accounts-payable detail that converted as a summary instead of open invoices and bills, inventory re-based onto a different costing method, and retained earnings or equity that shifted because the conversion closed the books differently than Desktop did. A related miss is the sales-tax-liability balance, which can land off when the agency setup converts differently. Most of these trace to data-integrity problems that existed in the Desktop file <em>before</em> conversion &mdash; which the automated tool carried over without flagging.</p>
      <p>One cause is structural rather than a bug: Desktop uses weighted-average costing and QuickBooks Online uses FIFO only, so the inventory asset and cost of goods sold legitimately change on conversion. The good news is that this is fixable, and you usually don&rsquo;t need to redo the migration. A diagnostic compares the converted Online file against your original Desktop balances, isolates exactly which accounts are off and why, and corrects them &mdash; opening balances, reconciliation, duplicates, AR/AP, inventory &mdash; until the file ties back to the numbers you trusted. Fixed-fee against a written scope. Independent ProAdvisor firm &mdash; not affiliated with Intuit Inc.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

